 rites, and other ceremonies of which gift-giving was an integral part. Recent anthropological interest in drawing a strong contrast between commodities and gifts both reflects and reinforces the conception of the gift as part of the giver and the related distinction between the realm of the gift and the realm of the marketplace. The author argues that Japanese practices of giving and receiving challenge assumptions related to this idea of the gift.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAnthropology -- Asia. 4aAnthropology -- Cultural and Social Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476699940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766999423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766999/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles